Project: Investigate a No Show Appointment Dataset¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

Rise in health-related issues has made it critical that everyone has easy access to health-care services. However, it has been discovered that despite providing access, patients may or may not show up for their appointments, resulting in hospital operating losses as salaries are paid whether or not patients visit the hospitals as expected. This report attempts to analyze the reasons why patients do not show up for appointments after scheduling them, as well as provide potential solutions that hospitals can consider in order to increase revenue. This dataset collects information from 100,000 plus medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row. The dataset is made up of 14 unique variables which we are going to use for our analysis.

Variables in this Dataset¶

1) "Scheduled Day" = tells us on what day the patient set up their appointment.

2) "Neighborhood" = indicates the location of the hospital.

3) "Scholarship" = indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in the Brasilian welfare program "Bolsa Família".

4) "Patient ID" = indicates the patient's number used in indentiification at the hospital.

5) "Appointment ID" = indicates the appointment number given to each patient.

6) "Gender" = indicates whether the patient is a Male or Female.

7) "Appointment Day" = indicates the patient's date of appointment.

8) "Age" = indicates the age of the patient.

NB//: 1) No Show variable will be used as our dependent variable while the others will be used as independent variables

2) For the last column: it says ‘No’ if the patient showed up to their appointment, and ‘Yes’ if they did not show up.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

So we will try answering the following questions below:

1) Comparing the percentage of people that showed up to those that didn't?

2) Why are people not showing up for their appointments?

3) Is scholarship a major determinant in affecting the presence of the patient at the hospital?

4) Is there any significant relationship between distance from patient neighbourhood to the hospital and their showing up for appointments?

5) Any impact on the ability of a patient to show up for their appointment using time difference between a patient schedule date and his appointment date?

#115 is the oldest age according to the box plot and that seems like a realistic age for a human being

# Implementing a function statement to rectify the discrepancy

def outlier(df, age):
    
    q1 = df['Age'].quantile(0.25)
    
    q3 = df['Age'].quantile(0.75)
    
    QR = q3 - q1
    
    df = df.loc[~((df['Age'] < (q1 -1.5 * QR))| (df['Age'] < (q3 + 1.5 * QR))),]
    
    return df

outlier(df, 'Age')

# Defining a percent function

def percent (value):
    percent = round(df[value].value_counts()/len(df)*100)
    return percent

# Creating a function to analyze the scholarship variable

def val(variable):
    chel = df[variable].value_counts()
    df1 = chel.plot(kind = 'bar', figsize = (12,8))
    plt.title("Count of Free Medicals")
    plt.ylabel("Counts")
    plt.xlabel("{}".format(variable))
    return df1

So Using the chart above, it shows that there is a direct relationship between waiting time and patients ability to show up.

Majority of patient called in on the 3rd of May 2016 while majority of appointment was fixed on the 16th of May 2016.

Analyzing the difference between schedule and appointment shows that 25 percentile had the same day call up while some patient had to wait for as long as 179 days after scheduling an appointment.

It can be observed that those with shorter waiting time show up more than those with longer waiting time.

Conclusions¶

So during my analysis of this dataset, I was able to come up with the following findings:

1) Scholarship had no impact on the ability of patient to show up for their appointments and this can be due to the affordability of the medical bill in brazil

2) Patient with shorter waiting time tend to show up for their appointment more than does with longer waiting time. This shows that an increase in wait time results in the possibility of having a decrease in the number of patient showing u at the facility

3)20 % of the total populations didn't show up for their appointments.

Limitations¶

1) If possible the hospital can help expand my analysis by providing more information on the major issue that prompt patients to book appointments

2) It looks like the data collection time is a bit too small to make predictions as regards patients no-show up factor.
